    "body": "@romani \r\n> do we really need support of checkstyle_packages.xml - https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/blob/master/src/xdocs/config.xml#L761 ?\r\n\r\nWe use this file to specify which packages to scan for 3rd party modules at https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/blob/46fa8090954480eecdeb6e7367f0e30655853f42/src/main/java/com/puppycrawl/tools/checkstyle/PackageNamesLoader.java#L137-L147 .\r\n\r\nIf you are asking why don't we pull in all modules in the full classpath instead of restricting to a list of packages from users, than the only good reasons I have not to do it are:\r\n* Error message will be slightly more vague as it won't say what packages we were looking at. See: https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/pull/4886 which we just updated recently\r\n* Scanning the entire classpath could take longer as we will be looking at more classes and not restricting any by package.\r\n\r\nI will look into the second point.",

    "body": "@romani \r\n> do we really need support of checkstyle_packages.xml - https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/blob/master/src/xdocs/config.xml#L761 ?\r\n\r\nWe use this file to specify which packages to scan for 3rd party modules at https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/blob/46fa8090954480eecdeb6e7367f0e30655853f42/src/main/java/com/puppycrawl/tools/checkstyle/PackageNamesLoader.java#L137-L147 .\r\n\r\nIf you are asking why don't we pull in all modules in the full classpath instead of restricting to a list of packages from users, than the only good reasons I have not to do it are:\r\n* Error message will be slightly more vague as it won't say what packages we were looking at. See: https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle/pull/4886 which we just updated recently\r\n* Scanning the entire classpath could take longer as we will be looking at more classes and not restricting any by package.\r\n\r\nI will look into the second point.",

    "author_association": "COLLABORATOR",
    "body": "Clemens,\r\n\r\nThank for your review and comments.\r\nI apologize for the delay in replying.\r\n\r\nCan you clarify please - why condition  root.waitThis().size() > 0  (....not OR EQUAL)?\r\n\r\nLockGraphManager placed graph nodes on levels, calculate level \"width\" for visualisation and so on.\r\n\r\nThe source of nodes is the plugin of specific databases, at this moment - Postgres, Oracle and Exasol but this is not a final list (I hope) and in the future for other DBs there may be a situation of a \"degenerated\" graph that will consist of only one root node. In this case condition \"root.waitThis().size() >= 0\" cant be replaced with \"root.waitThis().size() > 0\". In other words I guess condition \"root.waitThis().size() >= 0\" now is not necessary at all - because its always true :) This is a legacy of LockGraphManager version of the manager that could not build degenerate graphs.\r\n\r\nCan you fix your PR or I can create patch too.\r\n\r\nThanks again for the review.\r\nAndrew.",

    "body": "#1319 overrode the configuration (I merged it, funny enough).\n\nBut to add a (working) graphite reporter, one doesn't need to touch any java code:\n- Add dependency to pom\n\n``` xml\n<dependency>\n    <groupId>io.dropwizard</groupId>\n    <artifactId>dropwizard-metrics-graphite</artifactId>\n</dependency>\n```\n- and then add the reporter to the yaml\n\n``` yaml\nmetrics:\n  reporters:\n    - type: graphite\n      host: localhost\n      port: 2003\n      prefix: my-awesome-service\n```\n\nSo at this point, I think the example application is _wrong_, unless @joschi remembers why it was done 8 months ago.\n",

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "#1319 overrode the configuration (I merged it, funny enough).\n\nBut to add a (working) graphite reporter, one doesn't need to touch any java code:\n- Add dependency to pom\n\n``` xml\n<dependency>\n    <groupId>io.dropwizard</groupId>\n    <artifactId>dropwizard-metrics-graphite</artifactId>\n</dependency>\n```\n- and then add the reporter to the yaml\n\n``` yaml\nmetrics:\n  reporters:\n    - type: graphite\n      host: localhost\n      port: 2003\n      prefix: my-awesome-service\n```\n\nSo at this point, I think the example application is _wrong_, unless @joschi remembers why it was done 8 months ago.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "> Why aren't we using https://connect2id.com/products/nimbus-jose-jwt \r\n\r\nTo be honest, I don't have a perfectly valid excuse. I didn't come across it in the beginning when looking through candidate libraries and as such evaluated only jjwt which lacks support for JDK9+ and java-jwt whis is only tested with java 8. Also, we have been traditionally reluctant to bringing in dependencies and the scope of this work seemed to be just not large enough to justify the effort. Finally, there will not be any need to implement cryptographic primitives here, so I evaluated the risk of a significant implementation error to be low enough. \r\n\r\nStill, I will not object too much if we feel like `nimbus-jose-jwt` is a better option. I've come across the implementation lately, when looking into JWE implementations and I think it's a solid one. The only \"issue\" I see is that it depends on [`json-smart`](https://netplex.github.io/json-smart) which we would need to bring in also. Can I elicit additional opinions here: @jaymode , @tvernum  ?\r\n\r\n> I noticed it is already pulled in as a transitive dependency prob for kerberos ./gradlew :x-pack:plugin:security:dependencies\r\n\r\nWe use it as a test dependency only, for Kerberos tests, we don't ship it with Elasticsearch. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "> we do not describe how we write objects to the repository, so after adding this I think users will still struggle to understand the implications of the various options for storage_class. I'm not sure if we want to describe the repository layout in enough detail to address this.\r\n\r\nI don't think that we should describe how we write objects to the repository and I don't think it would help anyway. But I think it is valuable for users to understand the implication of changing the storage class on an existing repository, ie that the storage class is applied to new snapshotted files only. The explanation of incremental snapshots looks sufficient to me.\r\n\r\n> I do not think we should explicitly recommend setting all objects to the same storage class. It makes the most sense to me, but the choice of storage class is irrelevant to Elasticsearch, and I think users should feel free to set it to whatever they want according to their usage.\r\n\r\nI agree that the choice of storage class is out of scope and I don't think this change recommend to use a specific storage class? I still think that we must indicate a) what is the default storage class, b) changing the setting on an existing repository only change the storage class for newly created objects resulting in a mixed usage of storage classes in the repo and c) users may prefer use Lifecycle Policies to manage storage classes.",
